S.B. 97
SENATE BILL NO. 97–COMMITTEE ON COMMERCE AND LABOR
(ON BEHALF OF THE JOINT INTERIM STANDING COMMITTEE
ON HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES)
PREFILED JANUARY 14, 2025
____________
Referred to Committee on Commerce and Labor
SUMMARY—Makes revisions to the Silver State Health Insurance
Exchange. (BDR 57-346)
FISCAL NOTE: Effect on Local Government: No.
Effect on the State: Contains Appropriation not included
in Executive Budget.
~
EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to health insurance; requiring the Executive
Director of the Silver State Health Insurance Exchange to
apply for a federal waiver to allow certain persons to
access health plans offered on the Exchange; expanding
the number of voting members of the Board of Directors
of the Exchange; making an appropriation; and providing
other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law establishes the Silver State Health Insurance Exchange to facilitate
2 the purchase of subsidized health plans by certain small employers and natural
3 persons who are citizens of the United States or otherwise lawfully present in the
4 United States. (Chapter 695I of NRS) Section 1 of this bill requires the Executive
5 Director of the Exchange, in collaboration with the Director of the Department of
6 Health and Human Services, the Director of the Department of Business and
7 Industry and the Commissioner of Insurance, to: (1) apply for a federal waiver to
8 authorize any natural person to purchase a qualified health plan on the Exchange,
9 regardless of his or her immigration status, if the natural person otherwise qualifies
10 to purchase such a plan on the Exchange; and (2) conduct, or contract with an
11 independent actuary to conduct, an actuarial analysis before applying for the waiver
12 to ensure that such waiver will comply with certain federal requirements. (42
13 U.S.C. § 18052(b)) Section 2 of this bill makes a conforming change to indicate
14 that the waiver, if approved, would authorize natural persons who are not lawfully
15 present in the United States to purchase qualified health plans. Section 4 of this bill
16 makes an appropriation of $1,000,000 to the Exchange for the costs of the actuarial
-
